                <h1 class="post caption">Basal Cell Carcinoma</h1>
                <p class="text">A dermatofibroma is a common benign fibrous nodule usually found on the skin of the
                    lower legs.</p>
                <p class="text">A dermatofibroma is also called a cutaneous fibrous histiocytoma.</p>
                <p class="text">Dermatofibromas are mostly seen in adults. People of every ethnicity can develop
                    dermatofibromas. Ordinary dermatofibromas are more common in women than in men, although some
                    histologic variants are more commonly identified in males.</p>
                <p class="text">It is not clear if dermatofibroma is a reactive process or a true neoplasm. The lesions
                    are composed of proliferating fibroblasts. Histiocytes may also be involved.</p>
                <p class="text">They are sometimes attributed to minor trauma including insect bites, injections, or a
                    rose thorn injury, but not consistently. Multiple dermatofibromas can develop in patients with
                    altered immunity such as HIV, immunosuppression, or autoimmune conditions.</p>
